    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-02-11T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-02-11T12:00:00-05:00" n="705"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d705">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.7393 C 73/40: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-02-11T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 11, 1930—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>52. Legation’s 57, January 17, noon. Commercial Pacific Cable Company informs
                    Department it has been requested by Chinese Government to send a representative
                    to China to negotiate renewal of landing rights in China for its cable. Company
                    states it is sending William J. Deegan, Vice President, and Maynard Dodd,
                    General Superintendent, to negotiate renewal. These men are due to arrive in
                    Shanghai early in March. Please render them all appropriate assistance. Inform
                    Shanghai. See Department’s instruction of October 26, 1925.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d705fn2">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cotton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
